{"title":"Thinking Across Scales","markdown":{"yaml":{"title":"Thinking Across Scales","subtitle":"An unfinished manifesto","date":"2026-07-07","format":{"html":{"page-layout":"article"}},"categories":["Philosophy","Ecology","Systems Thinking"]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n> Every landscape is also a way of thinking.\n\nWe often explain problems at the scale of individuals, when their roots lie in larger systems. We debate policies at the national level, yet rarely ask how they are lived by a single person. Thinking Across Scales is the practice of moving continuously between these perspectives—between individuals and institutions, places and planets, moments and millennia. Ecological problems are fundamentally problems of scale. I have come to believe that life is, too.\n\nI did not arrive at this idea through philosophy.\n\nI arrived through fieldwork.\n\nYears of ecological investigations across China's forests, wetlands, grasslands, and mountains slowly revealed a recurring pattern.\n\nThe questions I carried into the field were rarely the questions I brought home.\n\nA fallen tulip tree became a story about institutions.\nA cigarette butt became a story about policy.\nA wetland became a story about time.\n\nThe Ecology of the Mind is my attempt to continue these conversations.\n\nIt is not a travel blog.\n\nIt is not an academic website.\n\nIt is a living collection of journeys, essays, conversations, and ideas exploring how landscapes shape the ways we think—and how our ways of thinking, in turn, reshape the landscapes we inhabit.\n\nThis is where the journey begins.","srcMarkdownNoYaml":"\n> Every landscape is also a way of thinking.\n\nWe often explain problems at the scale of individuals, when their roots lie in larger systems. We debate policies at the national level, yet rarely ask how they are lived by a single person. Thinking Across Scales is the practice of moving continuously between these perspectives—between individuals and institutions, places and planets, moments and millennia. Ecological problems are fundamentally problems of scale. I have come to believe that life is, too.\n\nI did not arrive at this idea through philosophy.\n\nI arrived through fieldwork.\n\nYears of ecological investigations across China's forests, wetlands, grasslands, and mountains slowly revealed a recurring pattern.\n\nThe questions I carried into the field were rarely the questions I brought home.\n\nA fallen tulip tree became a story about institutions.\nA cigarette butt became a story about policy.\nA wetland became a story about time.\n\nThe Ecology of the Mind is my attempt to continue these conversations.\n\nIt is not a travel blog.\n\nIt is not an academic website.\n\nIt is a living collection of journeys, essays, conversations, and ideas exploring how landscapes shape the ways we think—and how our ways of thinking, in turn, reshape the landscapes we inhabit.\n\nThis is where the journey begins."},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":false,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":"none","code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":false,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-tools":false,"tbl-colwidths":"auto","merge-includes":true,"inline-includes":false,"preserve-yaml":false,"latex-auto-mk":true,"latex-auto-install":true,"latex-clean":true,"latex-min-runs":1,"latex-max-runs":10,"latex-makeindex":"makeind